I really think (because this thread is 6 month older) that you already solved your problem but for the new guys:

You must do it with java JDK 11 (until now);
I just tried version 16 but it still doesn&#39;t work (so you must remove it from you machine).

There is already [`isNullOrEmpty`][1] function in **Kotlin** for Collections. It is defined like the following:

    @SinceKotlin(&quot;1.3&quot;)
    @kotlin.internal.InlineOnly
    public inline fun &lt;T&gt; Collection&lt;T&gt;?.isNullOrEmpty(): Boolean {
        contract {
            returns(false) implies (this@isNullOrEmpty != null)
        }
    
        return this == null || this.isEmpty()
    }

So if you have an object of type `List?` you can use it like the following:

    val list: List&lt;String&gt;? = ... // somehow get the list
    if (list.isNullOrEmpty()) {
        // do something when the list is null or empty
    }


----------
If you want to create your own function for the `List` object in **Kotlin** you can create an [**extension function**][2] on `List` type:

    fun &lt;T&gt; List&lt;T&gt;?.hasAtLeastTwoElements(): Boolean = this != null &amp;&amp; size &gt;= 2

And then you can use it:

    val list: List&lt;String&gt;? = ... // somehow get the list
    if (list.hasAtLeastTwoElements()) {
        // do something when the list has at least two elements
    }


  [1]: https://kotlinlang.org/api/latest/jvm/stdlib/kotlin.collections/is-null-or-empty.html
  [2]: https://kotlinlang.org/docs/extensions.html

